<HEADLINE> Jordanian King Launches Phone Diplomacy on Camp David Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian King Abdullah Bin Hussein
on Friday launched an extensive telephone diplomacy to reaffirm
Jordan's support for the Palestinians and to protect Jordan's
interests in the on-going trilateral summit at David Camp near
Washington.
</P>
<P>
The monarch held telephone conversations with Egyptian President
Hosni Mubarak, Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak, Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat to discuss the summit set to resolve the most
difficult issues between Israel and the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
In his call to Arafat, King Abdullah stressed Jordan supports
the efforts by the Palestinians to achieve a just and peaceful
solution, which will meet the aspirations of the Arab nation and to
achieve the rights of the Palestinians, including the establishment
of an independent state.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, Abdullah received a phone call from Barak,
who briefed the monarch on the latest developments of the three-way
summit between Barak himself, Arafat and U.S. President Bill
Clinton which was launched on July 11.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah stressed to Barak the importance to Jordan and all
countries and peoples in the region that the summit succeed and
make progress to open the way to a lasting and just peace
agreement.
</P>
<P>
The king also consulted with Egyptian leader Mubarak on the
David Camp summit, and both leaders stressed that any solutions
must lead to a just, durable and comprehensive peace in the region.
</P>
<P>
Egypt and Jordan signed a peace treaty with Israel in 1979 and
1994 respectively, and currently they are the only two Arab
countries to reach such a peace deal with the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, Jordanian Foreign Minister Abdel Ilah Khatib
said Jordan is closely following the development of the David Camp
summit, which focused on the thorniest issues of Jerusalem,
Palestinian refugees, border and security arrangements.
</P>
<P>
Khatib stressed that Jordan has a stake in the final status
issues between Israel and the Palestinians, particularly in the
refugee issue, because it is hosting some 1.5 million Palestinian
refugees.
</P>
<P>
And also, the status of Jerusalem is not related to only one
party, but to Jordan and other countries in the Arab world, as well
as the whole Muslim and Christianity world, Khatib added.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian government supports Palestinian refugees' rights to
choose between returning home or staying in Jordan while asking for
compensations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
