<HEADLINE> Diabetes a Growing Threat in Gulf: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Diabetes has occurred in up to 17
percent of the overall population in the Gulf region while at least
11 percent more are likely to develop the disease in the future,
according to studies in various Gulf countries.
</P>
<P>
"The most startling fact of all is that Type 1 diabetes, which
is more common among children and adolescents, is as high as 20
percent (of the total incidence), one of the highest in the world,"
said Dr. Abdul Razak Al Madani, secretary-general of the Dubai-
based Gulf Diabetes Study Group.
</P>
<P>
Al Madani said the soaring incidence of diabetes among children
in the past few year is especially alarming. The Gulf is considered
among the world's dangerous spots for diabetes, reported local
media on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The Gulf Diabetes Group has representatives from the United Arab
Emirates, Saudi Arabia, Qatar, Kuwait, Bahrain and Oman. Two
doctors from each country are on the board. The aim of the group is
to promote services concerning diabetes and create awareness of the
risk among the general public. 
</P>
</TEXT>
