<HEADLINE> Relatives of Malvinas War Victims Present Lawsuit Against Britain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The commission announced Saturday in a communique that it is
preparing to file a lawsuit before the Human Rights European Court.
</P>
<P>
It said that although the Court rejected this week an
accusation made for the same reasons by two relatives of the
fallen, this does not mean that most of the relatives of the
fallen in the Belgrano grouped in this commission cannot present
their own lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
The commission said in its communique that on the contrary, the
court rejection has stimulated it to continue with the
denunciation.
</P>
<P>
Two relatives of the fallen in the Malvinas War filed an
accusation against Britain for war crimes, which was rejected by
the Human Rights European Court "because it was presented
belatedly," and "internal procedures had not been exhausted."
</P>
<P>
The Argentine cruiser General Belgrano received on May 2, 1982,
the impact of two torpedoes launched by the Conqueror nuclear
submarine, whose commander was authorized to start the attack by
the then British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher.
</P>
<P>
The attack caused 323 Argentine crewmen dead.  
</P>
</TEXT>
