<HEADLINE> Brazilian Tourists Spend More Money Abroad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Central Bank data quoted Saturday by the press show that raw
expenditures in January to June international trips amounted to 1.
77 billion U.S. dollars, 23.8 percent over the amount recorded in
the first semester of 1999, when the figure was 1.42 billion
dollars.
</P>
<P>
In June Brazilians spent 362 million dollars on trips and
purchases abroad, against 276 million dollars spent in the same
month of 1999.
</P>
<P>
Liquid disbursement, which is the money spent by Brazilians
abroad increased 46.38 percent, compared to the first half of 1999,
going from 569 million dollars to 833 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
A Central Bank analysis shows that tourists expenditures in
1999 were strongly influenced by the uncertainty caused by the
devaluation of the Brazilian currency. The uncertainty was
surmounted this year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
