<DOCNO> XIE20000722.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexico Controls Demographic Growth: President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Mexico has now 97.4 million residents.
</P>
<P>
Zedillo said that the growth rate of the population was 2.1
percent per year in 1994, when he assumed the presidency of the
country.
</P>
<P>
His government set itself the target in 1995 of reducing the
rate of growth, and according to a recent report on the census of
the last decade, the birth rate dropped to 1.75 percent.
</P>
<P>
Zedillo said Saturday in his weekly radio program "A chat with
the President," that the birth rate reduction obeys, among other
things, to the fact that more couples use some method of family
planning.
</P>
<P>
Ninety-nine percent of Mexicans enjoy now health assistance
coverage and life expectancy has risen to a 75 years on average,
he added.
</P>
<P>
He also said that his administration promoted the development
of small cities to better distribute the population in the
territory and create new poles for investment.
</P>
<P>
The drop in the birth rate opens new opportunities for
development, because it permits to direct more federal resources
to the improvement of public services, said Zedillo.  
</P>
</TEXT>
