<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S., British Warplanes Bomb Southern Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, July 22 (Xinhua) -- U.S. and British warplanes on
Saturday attacked civilian installations in southern Iraq and were
challenged by Iraqi anti-aircraft artillery, an Iraqi military
spokesman said here.
</P>
<P>
In a statement carried by the official Iraqi News Agency (INA),
the spokesman said that at 0925 local time (0525 GMT), 11
formations of U.S. and British planes made 19 armed sorties over
the southern provinces of Basra, Misan Thi-Qar, Qadissiyah, Wasit,
Muthana and Najaf.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi air defense opened fire at the aggressing planes and
forced them to flee to their bases in Saudi Arabia and Kuwait, it
said.
</P>
<P>
Iraq claims that bombings by the U.S. and British jets have
killed 300 civilians and injured nearly 1,000 others since December
1998, when the U.S. and Britain launched the four-night Operation
Desert Fox air strikes against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The United States and Britain are imposing and patrolling two
no-fly zones in the north and south of Iraq in what they claim to
be an effort to protect the Kurdish population in the north and the
Shiite Muslims in the south from what they called Baghdad's
possible persecution.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has declared that it does not recognize these zones and
vowed to continue confronting any allied planes violating its
airspace. 
</P>
</TEXT>
