<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran, Germany Express Interest in Expansion of Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Iran and Germany here on Saturday
expressed their willingness to expand bilateral ties, especially
cooperation in economic fields, the Islamic Republic News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
Iran is ready to expand relations with Germany in all areas
based on mutual respect and common interests, Iranian First Vice
President Hassan Habibi told visiting German Minister of Labor and
Social Affairs Walter Riester.
</P>
<P>
Habibi said Iran welcomes Germany to actively participate in the
country's economic activities. The two countries can expand
cooperation by holding regular meetings on employment, investments
and technical and vocational training, he added.
</P>
<P>
He also called for the exchange of know-how on privatization and
international marketing.
</P>
<P>
The German labor minister, who arrived here Friday, called a
recent trip by President Mohammad Khatami to Germany as "positive,"
saying the trip has brought about good impression among the German
public and media.
</P>
<P>
He added Germany is interested in bolstering bilateral ties with
Iran in all areas, especially in the transfer of technical know-
how, establishment of vocational training centers and training of
Iranian economic experts.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, the German minister also held a meeting with
his Iranian counterpart Hussein Kamali, during which both officials
stressed their readiness to expand bilateral cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Kamali told the German visitor that he is happy with the
expansion of bilateral relations and added that President Khatami's
recent visit to Berlin showed the political will on both sides to
expand the cooperation in all areas.
</P>
<P>
Riester said he is happy to visit Iran, underlining the
necessity of expanding bilateral relations in economic areas.
</P>
<P>
The Germany minister's visit came only eight days after
President Khatami ended his three-day landmark visit to Berlin, the
first by an Iranian president since the 1979 Islamic revolution.
</P>
<P>
Khatami, who received a warm welcome in Germany, said he was
satisfied with his visit, hopeful that good Tehran-Berlin ties
would have a favorable impact on Iran's ties with the European
Union.
</P>
<P>
Tehran and Berlin are determined to expand relations in all
spheres, he said at the end of his visit on July 13.
</P>
<P>
Germany was once Iran's largest trading partner, but the status
was taken by Italy in recent years due to strains in Tehran-Berlin
ties after a German court ruled in 1997 that the Iranian government
had been involved in the assassination of exiled Iranian dissidents
in Germany. 
</P>
</TEXT>
