<HEADLINE> Egypt, Jordan Urge Israel to Return East Jerusalem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Egypt and Jordan stressed on Saturday
East Jerusalem is part of the Arab territories occupied by
Israel in 1967 and subject to the relevant United Nations
resolutions that demand Israel to return those lands.
</P>
<P>
Arab countries see East Jerusalem as subject to the U.N.
Resolution 242 because it was occupied by Israel in 1967, Jordanian
Foreign Minister Abdel Ilah al-Khatib said after meeting with his
Egyptian counterpart Amr Moussa in Alexandria.
</P>
<P>
Moussa, who was speaking to reporters along with al-Khatib,
underlined the Arab stand on the issue of East Jerusalem is
final and is one that insists on the liberation of this land.
</P>
<P>
He said Jerusalem is holy to Muslims, a fact that justifies
the aspiration of the Arabs and the Muslims all over the world for
complete control over Arab East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The two foreign ministers expressed hope the summit between
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat and Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak at Camp David in the United States since July 11 can lead to
a final agreement on a fair peace.
</P>
<P>
On the issue of Palestinian refugees, al-Khatib said any
agreement should consider the nearly 1.5 million refugees living in
Jordan, as well as the rights of Jordan that has been
hosting refugees for 50 years.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak and Jordanian King Abdullah,
whose countries made peace with Israel in 1979 and 1994
respectively, held a telephone conversation on Friday to discuss
the Camp David summit. They called for a settlement that will
guarantee the Palestinians' legitimate rights, including that to
establish a state with East Jerusalem as its capital.
</P>
<P>
Al-Khatib, who arrived in Egypt's Mediterranean port city for a
brief visit, said the two leaders are due to meet within the coming
days to further discuss the Middle East peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
