<HEADLINE> Iraq Denies U.S. Allegation on Kuwaiti MIAs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Iraq has denied the U.S. accusation
that it is obstructing the work of the International Committee of
the Red Cross (ICRC) on the Kuwaiti missings in action (MIAs), the
official Iraqi News Agency (INA) reported on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to the Unites States Senate and Congress, Iraqi
National Assembly (parliament) Speaker Saadoun Hamadi said Iraq
will welcome the ICRC to Iraq "at any time" to settle the issue of
Kuwaiti MIAs during Iraq's 1990 invasion of Kuwait and the ensuing
Gulf War in 1991.
</P>
<P>
Hamadi said Iraq has released all the Kuwaiti prisoners since
the ceasefire in 1991.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Hamadi accused the Kuwaiti authorities of concealing
the truth over the fate of 1,150 missing Iraqis.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has set up a "popular committee" to investigate the fate of
those Iraqis missing in the Gulf War. Neighboring Kuwait has a
similar committee to investigate the whereabouts of more than 600
Kuwaitis and other Arabs who went missing.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait has denied it still holds any Iraqis.
</P>
<P>
Iraq admits it took prisoners after its occupation forces were
evicted from Kuwait, but says it lost track of them during an
uprising in southern Iraq after the Gulf War. 
</P>
</TEXT>
