<HEADLINE> Ethiopians Urged to Fight against Rape </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, July 22 (Xinhua) -- A senior Ethiopian official
has urged all walks of life to work closely in the fight against
rape, which has become a serious social vice in the country.
</P>
<P>
Tadelech Haile-Michael, head of the Women's Affairs Section in
the Office of the Prime Minister, told a national workshop on rape
and abduction organized by the Ethiopian Psychologists'
Association (EPA) Friday, that psychologists in particular had the
responsibility of preventing the prevalence of rape through
raising public awareness on their negative impacts and providing
counseling services for the victims.
</P>
<P>
According to Tadelech, the government was exerting utmost
efforts to ensure women's rights of equality.
</P>
<P>
She said the adoption of the National Women's Affairs Policy
and the new Family Law are testimony to the government's
determination to bring an end to discrimination against women.
</P>
<P>
According to EPA officials, sexual abuse is becoming rampant
particularly in the rural parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
A report from the Federal Police Commission of Ethiopia shows
that three young girls are raped every day in the country.
</P>
<P>
A total of 689 young girls and 412 adult women were raped in
the first half of this year, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The police commission pointed out that the figures could double
if all rapes were reported, saying threats and stigmatization are
the main reasons why rape victims do not report such violence to
the police. 
</P>
