<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Takes Measures to Curb River Blindness </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopia has established a
national task force designed to curb the spread of river blindness,
a common disease in the country, local press reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Danile Kebede, coordinator of the task force, was quoted as
saying that in addition to the Ethiopian Health Ministry,
professionals from the World Health Organizations and other
international medical institutions would get involve in the
activities.
</P>
<P>
According to Danile, a study would be carried out during the
next five years with a cost of six million U.S. dollars in regions
where river blindness has been rampant, adding that more than one
million people in Ethiopia are affected by the disease.
</P>
<P>
River blindness is a bacterial disease transmitted by flies
hatched in rivers. It causes painful skin irritation and leads
some people to go blind. People living along river banks are
particularly prone to the disease. 
</P>
</TEXT>
