<DOCNO> XIE20000722.0028 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> (Update with more details)U.S. PAC-3 Missile Again Hits Target Missile </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The PAC-3, an improved version of the Patriots used against
Iraqi Scud missiles during the Gulf War in 1991, intercepted and
destroyed the incoming tactical ballistic missile target.
</P>
<P>
This was the fourth successful "hit-to-kill" intercept in a row
for the PAC-3 since the beginning of last year.
</P>
<P>
The test program for the new Patriot, part of the U.S. Theater
Missile Defense (TMD) system, will include another 13 shots at
different types of target missiles.
</P>
<P>
So far, the PAC-3 has successful completed six missions. The
first two were development tests with special instrument packages
instead of the seeker.
</P>
<P>
Unlike a planned U.S. National Missile Defense (NMD) effort to
protect the whole country from long-range attack, the theater
program is designed to protect U.S. troops and bases from short-
and medium-range "theater" missiles.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. plan to develop anti-missile interceptors violates the
1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile (ABM) treaty between Moscow and
Washington.
</P>
<P>
Arms control experts said the TMD and NMD, opposed by the
international community, will not only spark a new arms race, but
also threaten security and stimulate nuclear proliferation,
instead of promoting security and stemming the spread of nuclear
weapons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000722.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
