<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Belgium to Witness Big Fall in State Debt: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Belgium will witness a drastic
fall in its huge state debt in the next five years, according to
the latest forecasts by the country's High Finance Council, local
newspapers reported on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The forecast report, prepared for the government to draw up its
2001 budget in autumn, said that the debt ratio could fall to 85.7
percent of gross domestic product (GDP) by 2005, down from 114.3
percent of GDP at the end of 1999.
</P>
<P>
Since the launch of the euro, Belgium has rivaled Italy in the
euro zone as the country with the highest ratio of public debt to
GDP.
</P>
<P>
The latest projections also show the debt ratio falling below
100 percent of GDP in 2002, a year ahead of schedule, according to
a report in Belgian newspaper Financeel Economische Tijd.
</P>
<P>
The report of the High Finance Council confirmed that, thanks
to higher than expected growth in revenues, the government is
likely to balance its budget in 2000, two years earlier than
foreseen when the current budget was published last October.
</P>
<P>
Analysts say that the report is likely to reassure Belgium's
euro zone partners, which have urged the Belgian government to do
more to cut its debt, which peaked in 1993 at around 138 percent
of GDP. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
