<HEADLINE> Tauziat Out of French Olympic Team </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Nathalie Tauziat has been axed from
the French tennis team for the 2000 Sydney Olympic Games, the
board of directors of the French Tennis Federation (FFT) announced
on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Tauziat, who is planning retirement at the end of the year, is
still the second-highest ranked French woman player. Earlier this
year, she published a controversial autobiography "Women's Tennis
Stripped Bare", which is critical of some of her team mates.
</P>
<P>
The angry French women players met during Wimbledon Open to
demand the exclusion of 32-year-old Tauziat and the announcement
was made after a meeting in Rennes, where France are playing
Austria in a Davis Cup qualifying round match.
</P>
<P>
According to the FFT, Amelie Mauresmo, Sandrine Testud and
Nathalie Dechy will play for France in the women's singles in
Sydney in September with Testud partnering Julie Halard-Decugis in
the doubles.
</P>
<P>
The French men's team will comprise Nicolas Escude, Sebastien
Grosjean, Arnaud Clement and Arnaud Di Pasquale, with the doubles
combination to be selected from that quartet. 
</P>
