<HEADLINE> U.S. Enters Semifinals in Pan Am Basketball Worlds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 22 (Xinhua) -- The United States rallied from
behind to beat Argentina 83-78 Friday night in Ribeirao, Brazil,
entering the semifinals in the 2000 Confederation of Pan American
Basketball Association (COPABA) World Championship for Young Men
Qualifying Tournament.
</P>
<P>
With the help of three-point plays by Jason Richardson and
Kenny Satterfield in the final minutes, the United States managed
to keep their sheet clean with three straight wins, edging
Argentina (2-1) as the top seed in Group A.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. will play the host Brazil (2-1) on Saturday night who
lost Friday evening 96-87 to Dominican Republic (3-0). In the
other semifinal, the Dominican Republic will face Argentina.
</P>
<P>
"Argentina is probably the best team here, along with Brazil,
and we were in a dog fight from the beginning," said US head coach
Jim Boeheim, "It was just one of those games where we were never
able to get in front until right at the end. It was just a good,
hard fought team win."
</P>
<P>
Trailing most of the first half, including a 49-45 half-time
deficit, the United States took a two-point lead with four minutes
to go. Argentina missed its next three shots but grabbed the
rebound each time.
</P>
<P>
With 1:13 on the clock, Leiva scored two to put Argentina up by
three 78-75. However, those were Argentina's final points before
Richardson and Satterfield converted their three-point plays for a
hard victory for the United States.
</P>
<P>
Richardson led the U.S. team with 18 points and nine rebounds,
while Scola scored a game high 21 points in Argentina's losing
efforts.
</P>
<P>
In the other Group A action of the day, Puerto Rico topped
Canada 66-61 while Panama downed Uruguay 82-60 in Group B.
</P>
<P>
The winners of the semifinals will earn a qualifying berth in
next summer's World Championship and will compete for the gold
medal on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The losers of the semifinals will compete against each other
for the final qualifying spot from the American zone for the 2001
FIBA World Championship for Young Men which will be held in Japan.
</P>
</TEXT>
