<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 22 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
RIYADH -- Bahrain's telecommunications company Batelco signed a
2.2-million-U.S. dollars contract with the Middle East Logika
Company to operate a developed system for the service of the
Internet users in Bahrain.
</P>
<P>
The new system will provide customers with speedier access to
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- An agricultural technopark, called GAPROPARK, will be
built and operated by Turkish company Alarko Holding in the
country's southeast.
</P>
<P>
The project, which was introduced to government officials,
scholars, members of the parliament and businessmen Friday, was
prepared by Alarko Holding together with Lee Organization Inc. of
the United States.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkey's Aegean Textile Industrialists (EGS) joint
holding company will invest in e-commerce by setting up a network
on the Internet to market textile products.
</P>
<P>
EGS Executive Board Chairman Ismail Cansever announced in Izmir,
Turkey's southwestern industrial center, on Thursday that nearly 3,
000 companies will be involved in this network, adding that through
the network project, distribution of all kinds of products will be
possible.
</P>
<P>
Over the next three or four years the project will be completely
finished, he said.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- The Turkish government will issue an "ultimatum" to
order public institutions to pay their outstanding electricity
charges to the power supply company TEDAS.
</P>
<P>
Various public institutions owe some 426 trillion Turkish liras
(roughly 700 million U.S. dollars) to TEDAS.
</P>
<P>
If the public institutions still fail to pay their dues, the
Finance Ministry will either cut their budgetary allocations or
create additional funding at the worst.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the government must develop ways to improve TEAS's
productivity and reduce electricity losses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
