<HEADLINE> Pursuing Dialogue With DPRK Important: Russian FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OKINAWA, Japan, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Russian Foreign Minister
Igor Ivanov on Saturday stressed the importance of pursuing
dialogue with the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) not
only by Russia but also by other countries.
</P>
<P>
Russia will continue dialogue with Pyongyang, Ivanov said
during a meeting with his Japanese counterpart Yohei Kono, in Nago,
Okinawa Prefecture in southern Japan, according to Japanese
officials.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was held on the sidelines of the three-day annual
summit of the Group of Eight (G-8) major industrialized nations,
which entered the second day Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Ivanov was quoted as telling Kono that other countries should
follow suit to improve their relations with the DPRK by taking the
opportunity of emerging signs of detente on the Korean Peninsula
following the first-ever inter-Korean summit in Pyongyang last
month.
</P>
<P>
He briefed Kono on Russian President Vladimir Putin's visit to
Pyongyang earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
Kono was quoted as telling Ivanov that Japan, in cooperation
with the international community, wants to normalize its ties with
the DPRK.
</P>
<P>
Kono also spoke highly of the summit between DPRK leader Kim
Jong Il and South Korean President Kim Dae-jung in mid-June, the
Japanese officials said.
</P>
<P>
Kono and Ivanov agreed to make joint efforts to make Putin's
planned visit to Japan in early September successful, the
officials added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
