<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lopes, Chausson Win World Cup Dual Races </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 22 (Xinhua) -- American Brian Lopes and France's
Anne-Caroline Chausson won the World Cup mountain bike dual races
with victories in the 13th leg of the 16-round series in Arai on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Lopes, who placed 38th overall last season, collected his fifth
victory of the season by defeating Australian Wade Bootes in the
final and secured the overall title with two more dual races left
in the season. He topped the dual standings with a total of 265
points, 124 points ahead of second-placer Cedric Gracia of France.
</P>
<P>
Bootes was third overall with 127 points, followed by Scott
Beaumont of Britain with 109 points.
</P>
<P>
Chausson continued to dominate the women's dual event by
winning her fifth straight win out of six races.
</P>
<P>
Chausson, who missed to gain a point in the opener of the eight-
race dual category, won a one-on-one dual against American Leigh
Donovan to win the women's final.
</P>
<P>
Defending overall dual champion Chausson collected 50 points
for an unbeatable 250 points to retain the overall title.
</P>
<P>
Llanes earned 20 points for second overall place with 140
points, ahead of Donovan third with 135 points and Sabrina Jonnier
of France fourth with 125 points.
</P>
<P>
Sunday will see the men's and women's downhill races, sixth of
the eight-race category at the 13th leg of the 16-round mountain
bike series. 
</P>
</TEXT>
