<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Villagers Help Egrets Through Drought </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Some 350 Chinese villagers in
south China are now fighting a battle against a long-lasting
drought that threatens the survival of a group of wild egrets.
</P>
<P>
The campaign began three weeks ago, when some primary students
of Nalan Village in Yongning County in the Guangxi Zhuang
Autonomous Region, discovered two young egrets dead in a bamboo
grove near the village.
</P>
<P>
Soon, more egret deaths were reported, and the villagers
realized that they had died of starvation.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Yang'en, a 76-year-old villager of the Zhuang ethnic
group, said, "The ponds around our village have dried up, one
after another, leading to the disappearance of most fish and
shrimps."
</P>
<P>
To save the hundreds of local egrets, all the 350 villagers
pooled a total of 1,500 yuan (nearly 200 US dollars), almost the
total yearly income of a family there, to buy food for the egrets.
</P>
<P>
"We can't lose the egrets. They came to our village in the mid-
1980s, and have been helping us kill pests since then," said
villager Zhang Wenhui.
</P>
<P>
The local government has participated into the efforts to save
the egrets, but, according to experts, if the drought continues
the situation for egrets will get even worse.
</P>
<P>
"We will do our best to save the egrets," said Zhang Wenhui,
adding that his biggest wish at present is to have a whole-day
rainstorm. 
</P>
</TEXT>
