<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Turkish Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 22 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading Turkish newspapers on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Hurriyet (Freedom):
</P>
<P>
-- Four shepherds, who had set a forest fire in Buldan of
Turkey's southwestern province of Denizli, were sent to jail. The
fire burned 1,050 hectares of forests to ashes.
</P>
<P>
In violation of a government decree on closing forests to
prevent fires, Ali Dogru, Mehmet Aydogan, Irfan Aydogdu and Osman
Aydogdu set a picnic fire in the forest area and did not put it
out.
</P>
<P>
After being tried in court, the four were found guilty and
sentenced to imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
Milliyet (National):
</P>
<P>
-- The Turkish government is adopting certain measures to
minimize the negative effects of the energy shortage.
</P>
<P>
There will be limitations on the use of energy within the
framework of a "national mobilization" to maintain the balance
between electricity production and consumption.
</P>
<P>
Limitations will be imposed on window illuminations of shops,
street lights and buildings. The measures will be discussed at a
cabinet meeting on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Daily News:
</P>
<P>
-- The Western world in general and the European Union (EU) in
particular have been calling on Turkey to amend Article 312 of the
Turkish Penal Code (TCK) in a bid to broaden the scope of freedom
of expression.
</P>
<P>
Diplomatic sources in Ankara said that Turkey, which has been a
candidate for EU membership since December of last year, should do
something about the Turkish legal system, which curbs freedom of
expression. 
</P>
