<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia's International Reserves Decrease Slightly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's international
reserves decreased by 5 percent during the two weeks of July
compared with the figure by the end of last month.
</P>
<P>
The international reserves of Bank Neraga (central bank)
Malaysia amounted to 128.4 billion ringgit (33.8 billion U.S.
dollars) as on July 14, 2000 against 129.2 billion ringgit (34
billion U.S. dollars) as on June 30, 2000, the bank announced in a
statement Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The decrease in international reserves reflects higher debt
repayments and some outflows of portfolio capital, it said.
</P>
<P>
The underlying reserves position, however, remains strong, the
bank said, adding that of importance is that this reserves level
has been enhanced by strong trade flows and not by increases in
external borrowing.
</P>
<P>
The reserves are adequate to finance 5.7 months of retained
imports and amount to 6.5 times the short-term external debt, it
said.
</P>
<P>
According to the central bank, since August 1998, reserves have
increased by 13.6 billion U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
