<HEADLINE> S. Lanka Opposition Chief Withdraws From New Constitution Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNP leader Ranil Wickremesinghe was quoted as saying that he
would not take part in the talks with the government until police
conclude an investigation into his alleged links with separatist
Tamil Tiger rebels, who have been fighting a 17-year war against
the government in an attempt to create an independent Tamil state.
</P>
<P>
However, he added that other members of UNP will continue the
talks with the government.
</P>
<P>
The investigation was launched after state media reported early
this week that Wickremesinghe had met a senior member of Tamil
Tiger rebel group on a recent private visit to Singapore.
Wickremesinghe dismissed the alleged charges against him.
</P>
<P>
The new constitution hopefully to be adopted before the
parliament is dissolved on August 24 is aimed at isolating the
Tamil Tiger rebels from the minority Tamil community.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month the UNP and the ruling People's Alliance of
President Kumaratunga reached agreement on most parts of a draft
constitution which will devolve powers to provinces, including one
administered by Tamils. 
