<DOCNO> XIE20000722.0086 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bell Ranked First in Turkish Helicopter Bid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Turkey listed the U.S. Bell company
as its first option for co-production of 145 attack helicopters and
the Russian-Israeli consortium Kamov-IAI second, Anatolia News
Agency reported on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The vague announcement that the Bell has won Turkey's multi-
billion U.S. dollars defense project was made later on Friday
following a meeting of the Defense Industry Executive Committee
chaired by Turkish Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit.
</P>
<P>
Ecevit said that "as a result of our evaluations, it has been
understood that we had reached the level of contract negotiations.
The contract negotiations for production of 145 strike helicopters
will be held firstly with American Bell company, and secondly with
Russian-Israeli consortium Kamov-IAI in accordance with a priority
list."
</P>
<P>
He also tried to compose Italy's Agusta, the third bidder, by
saying that it would be "approached" if talks with the first two
groups proved "unsuccessful."
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that Ankara did not make a clear announcement of
one single winner for the tender, likely due to both political and
diplomatic consideration as well as desires to increase its bargain
chips.
</P>
<P>
It was no secret that when Turkey selected the winner of the 4
billion dollars tender, it had to make a tough choice between its
strategic ally the United States and regional rival Russia, which
has made a joint offer with Israel.
</P>
<P>
The winning company should also be elected by taking into
consideration such matters as local and joint production,
technology transfer and financing which can meet Turkey's
interests.
</P>
<P>
Because of difficulties in reaching a decision, the tender has
already been delayed four times.
</P>
<P>
Following Friday's decision, Ecevit said that "I want to state
that starting negotiations with the selected company would not mean
that we would carry out production with this company, and we would
absolutely accept the conditions put forward by this company."
</P>
<P>
He added that "we will never make concessions from the targets
of the project," referring to conditions in favor of Turkey, such
as technology transfer, selling to third countries and logistic
supports.
</P>
<P>
The premier expected to see the first helicopter of this co-
production project "in the second half of 2003."
</P>
<P>
After the last four meetings on the tender, France's Eurocopter
and U.S. Boeing company were eliminated. The three remaining
bidders, the Russian-Israeli Kamov/IAI, the Italian Agusta and the
U.S. Bell company have launched strong lobbyist activities to win
the tender.
</P>
<P>
While the Clinton administration and the U.S. lawmakers tried to
woo Ankara by praising the country in human rights and supporting
its efforts to join the European Union, senior officials from
Russia and Israel have gone to the Prime Ministry on several
occasions in recent days.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has geared up for the bid. This week, 38 American
senators wrote to Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, saying
that they were giving their full support for strong defense
cooperation between the U.S. and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Prior to Friday's announcement, some analysts suggested that the
U.S. Bell company has an important advantage in the tender.
</P>
<P>
They argued that apart from Washington's political weight,
Turkey's experience of U.S. arms purchases, working with Bell in
particular, will make the company a front-runner among the bidders.
</P>
<P>
Turkish-Italian relations have still not reached desired levels
since Rome refused to extradite Abdullah Ocalan, chieftain of the
outlawed separatist Kurdistan Workers Party (PKK) who hid himself
in Italy, to Turkey in 1998, they added.
</P>
<P>
They said that if Ankara gives the tender to the Russian
company, it will arouse criticism from within North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO), a U.S.-led western military alliance which
Turkey belongs to. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000722.0087 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Palestinian Official Denies Progress Made at Camp David </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GAZA, July 22 (Xinhua) -- No progress has been achieved on any
of the crucial issues being discussed at Camp David, said Secretary
General of the Executive Committee of Palestine Liberation
Organization (PLO) Mahmoud Abbas Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The gaps between the Palestinians and Israel are "still wide"
not only on the issue of Jerusalem also including the Palestinian
refugees, borders of a future Palestinian state and security, said
Abbas, who is also known as Abu Mazen.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the "Voice of Palestine" radio, Abbas, who
is currently at Camp David for the negotiations on a Palestinian-
Israeli peace deal, asserted that the Palestinian side strongly
opposes the postponement of resolving the final status issues,
particularly the fate of Jerusalem. Both sides want the holy city
as their capitals.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated the firm Palestinian stance over East Jerusalem,
which is occupied by Israel in the 1967 Middle East war, saying it
should be returned to the Palestinian sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian side cannot make any concessions on the issue
since it had already approved the U.N. Security Council Resolution
242, as well as Resolution 194 pertaining to the Palestinian
refugees and their return to their homeland, he said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the Palestinian leadership and the Palestinian
people cannot end the half-century conflict with Israel without
reaching a lasting solution, which is based on the Israeli pullout
to the borders before the 1967 war and the implementation of
relevant international resolutions.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian delegation rejected the U.S. and Israeli
proposals on sharing sovereignty over East Jerusalem, said Abbas,
reiterating that no agreement or peace can be made without the
return of the Arab East Jerusalem to the Palestinians. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000722.0088 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Releases Five Jailed Latvians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The President, K.R. Narayanan, commuted the five's life
sentence following an appeal by the Russian government, the PTI
quoted West Bengal Jail Minister Biswanath Chowdhury as saying.
</P>
<P>
The Latvians were released from the Presidency Jail in Calcutta
on Saturday morning under strict security and driven straight to
the Russian Consulate in the city, Chowdhury added.
</P>
<P>
The five, all crew members of a Russian AN-26 aircraft, were
accused of dropping a huge cache of arms and ammunition in Purulia
district of West Bengal on the night of January 17, 1995, and were
convicted of conspiring to wage war against the state in February
this year. They were sentenced to rigorous imprisonment for life.
</P>
<P>
The Russian government has made constant efforts to seek the
release of the five, and the Indian President's commutation came
ahead of Russian President Putin's scheduled visit to India in
October this year. 
</P>
