<HEADLINE> Philippines Seeks ILO Ratification of Pact Against Child Labor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Presidential adviser for children's affairs Anna Madrigal said
Saturday that the pact will protect children forced to work in
hazardous jobs such as mining, scavenging and firecracker
manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
She said on a TV program that Labor and Employment Secretary
Bienvenido Laguesma is now working for the ratification of the
pact by the International Labor Organization (ILO).
</P>
<P>
According to Madrigal, it can be an effective instrument to
fight the "worst forms of child labor" in the Philippines once it
is ratified.
</P>
<P>
"We also have laws versus child labor for kids under 15 and
those against exploitative labor," Madrigal said.
</P>
<P>
An ILO study showed that there are about 73 million child
laborers worldwide forced to engage in prostitution and slave away
in hazardous jobs in factories, mines and quarry pits.
</P>
<P>
Philippine National Red Cross Governor Rosa Rosal urged
lawmakers to come up with a law penalizing parents who force their
children to work. 
