<HEADLINE> Malaysian Trade Mission to Visit S. Korea, Japan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, July 22 (Xinhua) -- A Malaysian trade and
investment mission will visit South Korea and Japan from July 23
to August 1, the International Trade and Industry Ministry
announced here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Objectives of the mission to be led by International Trade and
Industry Minister Rafidah Aziz is aimed at enhancing trade and
investment with the two countries, the ministry said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
The 42-member mission will inform the business community in the
two countries trade and investment opportunities in Malaysia and
in multimedia activities in its Multimedia Super Corridor (MSC).
</P>
<P>
The mission would update the business community on Malaysia's
current economic progress and the status of various measures
undertaken by the Malaysian government to strengthen the economy.
</P>
<P>
Business meetings would be arranged to promote business
collaboration and joint ventures in areas such as automotive
components, computer peripherals, timber products, power utility
industry, garment industry, latex examination and surgical gloves
and industrial minerals.
</P>
<P>
The mission also seeks to export and trading opportunities for
special purpose vehicles, automotive components, computer
peripherals and timber products.
</P>
<P>
During the mission, Rafidah is scheduled to address the
business community of the two countries at seminars on "Business
Opportunities in Malaysia" in Seoul, in Fukuoka, Nagoya and
Yokohama.
</P>
<P>
South Korea was Malaysia's fifth largest trading partner in
1999 with trade amounting to 22.5 billion ringgit (5.92 billion U.
S.dollars) while Japan was Malaysia's second largest trading
partner in that year with trade totaling 89.1 billion ringgit (23.
44 billion U.S. dollars). 
