<HEADLINE> Manila Hopeful on Safe Release of Remaining Hostages </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Executive Secretary Ronaldo Zamora made it clear that the
government will still stick to its no-ransom policy, while making
sure a premium is placed on the hostages' safety.
</P>
<P>
"We are hopeful that we will succeed in our policy not to
launch military operations against the Abu Sayyaf. We will place a
premium on safety of the hostages and I think, after this, we will
correct whatever needs to be corrected," he said in a radio
interview.
</P>
<P>
The Abu Sayyaf, which released Friday four more Malaysians held
captive in Jolo island, Sulu, since April, is still holding 14 of
the 21 mostly foreign hostages kidnapped from neighboring Malaysia
's resort island of Sipadan on April 23. The group had earlier
released two Malaysians and one German woman.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the 14 hostages, Abu Sayyaf bandits have also in
their hands four French and German journalists, and 13 Filipino
Christian evangelists who went to their jungle lair in Jolo to
pray for the hostages.
</P>
<P>
Zamora made a fresh appeal to third parties not to offer ransom
for the release of hostages.
</P>
<P>
He said the Abu Sayyaf has shown its true colors during the
ongoing hostage negotiations by quietly dropping its political
demands.
</P>
<P>
The Abu Sayyaf had demanded, among other things, the creation
of an independent Islamic state and the protection of fishing
rights of the residents of Sulu.
</P>
<P>
"We have noticed that they are no longer pushing for their so-
called political demands. On our part, we have been consistent in
our position," he said. 
</P>
