<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus' Trade Deficit Grows </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus' trade deficit in the first
fourth months this year grew compared with the same period last
year, Cypriot newspapers reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Total exports during the January-April period amounted to 196.3
million Cyprus pounds (314.1 million U.S. dollars) while the
imports soared to 699.6 million pounds (1,119.4 million dollars),
with the trade deficit up to more than 503.0 million pounds (804.8
million dollars) from 447.7 million pounds (716.3 million dollars)
of the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Domestic exports and re-exports showed an increase, with
domestic exports reaching 81.0 million pounds (129.6 million
dollars) from 67.0 million pounds (107.2 million dollars) while
reexports rising to 115.0 million pounds (184.0 million dollars)
from 85 million pounds(136.0 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
Exports of industrial products, mainly pharmaceutical products,
clothing, cigarettes, cement and furniture, amounted to 61.0
million pounds (97.6 million dollars), accounting for nearly 80
percent of domestic exports.
</P>
<P>
Exports of raw agricultural products, mainly citrus fruit and
potatoes, amounted to 15.8 million pounds (25.3 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
Intermediate goods, consumer goods and transport equipment were
the major import items.
</P>
<P>
The European Union (EU) countries supplied Cyprus with goods
valued at 377.0 million pounds (603.2 million dollars) or 54
percent of total imports.
</P>
<P>
The EU absorbed 40.0 million pounds (64.0 million dollars) or
51.8 percent of total Cyprus domestic exports.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
