<DOCNO> XIE20000722.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Determined to Raise Oil Output </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Iraq is determined to raise its oil
output by self-reliance instead of oil contracts, the official
Iraqi News Agency (INA) reported on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Citing an official of the Iraqi oil ministry, the INA said that
even if Iraq does not conclude contracts with foreign companies to
develop oil fields, Iraq is still to raise its crude oil output.
</P>
<P>
Ever since 1998, Iraq has been implementing a wide-scale
development plan based on self-reliance to increase its oil
production, the INA said.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Oil Minister Amir Muhammad Rashid stated recently that
Iraq will upgrade its crude oil output to 3.5 million barrels per
day (bpd) by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
Iraq's current production stands at some 3.1 million bpd, of
which 600,000 barrels are consumed domestically and the rest for
exports.
</P>
<P>
Iraq's oil output has been gradually increasing. According to a
report released by the Middle East Economic Survey (MEES) on June
12, Iraq produced 3.03 million bpd in May, compared with 2.63
million bpd in April and 2.16 million bpd in March.
</P>
<P>
Despite this, Iraq has repeatedly claimed that its oil industry
hit by the decade-old sanctions is in a "critical" state because of
a shortage of oil equipment and spare parts.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Iraq has often accused the U.S. and British delegates
at the United Nations Sanctions Committee of blocking contracts it
signed with foreign countries to import food, medicine and oil
spare parts within the framework of the U.N. oil-for-food program.
</P>
<P>
Iraq said that only 21 percent of the oil contracts during the
past four phases of the U.N. oil-for-food deal were approved.
</P>
<P>
During the period, Iraq singed oil contracts worth 1.4 billion
U.S. dollars with foreign companies, but only 300 million dollars
worth of contracts were released.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has been under U.N. sanctions since its 1990 invasion of
Kuwait, but the U.N. oil-for-food accord allows Baghdad to export
crude in return for U.N.-supervised imports of humanitarian
supplies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
