<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0800 GMT, July 22 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OKINAWA, Japan -- U.S. President Bill Clinton is expected to
leave here for home a few hours earlier than scheduled on Sunday
after attending the Group of Eight summit in Nago, Okinawa
Prefecture.
</P>
<P>
Clinton will leave around noon Sunday, four to five hours
earlier than planned, to go back to the ongoing Middle East peace
talks at Camp David, Maryland, a Clinton aide said Saturday. The U.
S. president, who left Washington for Okinawa in the middle of a
summit between Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat and Israeli Prime
Minister Ehud Barak, was earlier scheduled to depart Okinawa at 4:
45 p.m. (0745 GMT) Sunday. (G8-Clinton)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BELGRADE -- Conclusive evidence shows that the killing of two
ethnic Albanians in Gnjilane, Kosovo, last July was committed by U.
S. soldiers rather than by Serbs, a military court in Gnjilane was
told Friday.
</P>
<P>
Thirty-five U.S. soldiers of the NATO-led peacekeeping force in
Kosovo on duty on the night of July 10,1999 have unanimously
testified that U.S. soldiers in an observation post shot and
killed the two Albanians, French international judge Patrice de
Charette told the court on Friday. He said the three Serb suspects
who were arrested that night and had been in custody in a U.S.
base prison near Gnjilane would be released soon, according to
Yugoslav state news agency Tanjug. (Yugoslavia-Kosovo-Killing)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The three-way Middle East peace talks at Camp
David near Washington slowed down on Friday with the beginning of
the Jewish Sabbath.
</P>
<P>
Following 11 days of intensive discussions, negotiators from
the U.S., Israel and Palestine had agreed to hold a pick-up
basketball game after sunset. Describing this as a "new
development," U.S. State Department spokesman Richard Boucher said
earlier Friday that "the teams will be mixed up between Americans,
Palestinians and Israelis, ... they're not divided up into sides."
Despite the lessening formality of the talks, Boucher said the
parties remained serious and committed to reaching a peace
agreement. (US-Mideast-Talks)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
OKINAWA, Japan -- Leaders of the Group of Eight (G-8) major
nations on Saturday adopted a charter to deal with the rapid
development of information technology at their second-day session
of the annual summit in Nago, Okinawa.
</P>
<P>
The "IT Charter" aims at promoting the growth of IT and IT-
derived macroeconomies and maximizing their positive economic
impacts, while setting up provisions to actively cope with
possible risks. The charter incorporates measures for seizing
opportunity and bridging the "digital divide" between rich and
poor people and countries. It also calls for efforts to forge
international rules on IT-related business activities. (G8-IT-
Charter) 
</P>
