<HEADLINE> Finding of First Direct Evidence of Tau Neutrino Hailed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Scientists Friday hailed the
finding of first direct evidence of the existence of tau neutrino
as a milestone in particle physics.
</P>
<P>
"It's a tremendous milestone," said Stanford University
physicist Martin Perl, winner of the 1995 Nobel Prize for
discovering the tau lepton, the first sign indicator for the tau
neutrino.
</P>
<P>
"Finding the tau neutrino is very important and very exciting."
</P>
<P>
Physicists at the U.S. Fermi National Accelerator Laboratory
announced Friday that they have produced the first direct evidence
for the tau neutrino, confirming the existence of an
extraordinarily elusive constituent of matter.
</P>
<P>
"This completes the picture of the subatomic constituents of
matter," said Phil Yager, a physicist at the University of
California at Davis, and a participant in the experiment.
</P>
<P>
"It's really important to see that this thing does in fact
exist and that it behaves the way we expected it to," he told
Xinhua in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
Yager said scientists can build another experiment that may
take physics beyond the Standard Model of elementary physics since
they can now detect the tau neutrino. "In the near future, there
is going to be a lot of even more exciting neutrino physics, " he
predicted.
</P>
<P>
The Standard Model postulates that virtually every conceivable
state of matter or energy can be embodied in a few particles and
the "matter particles" include six kinds of quarks, and six kinds
of leptons (The term lepton derives from the Greek word for "small
"). The neutrino resides in the lepton clan.
</P>
<P>
Earlier experiments had produced only indirect evidence for the
existence of the tau neutrino, which is massless or almost
massless, carries no electric charge and barely interacts with
surrounding matter.
</P>
<P>
The idea for the experiment that produced the neutrino evidence
came in 1994 from one of Yager's graduate students, Vittorio
Paolone, and a Fermilab physicist, Byron Lundberg.
</P>
<P>
The experiment was named Direct Observation of the Nu Tau, or
DONUT. Paolone, who was then a research physicist at University of
California at Davis, and Yager and others at Davis built a key
component of the experiment in 1995-1996.
</P>
<P>
Overall, 54 scientists were involved in pinning down the tau
neutrino, from 21 institutions and four countries, including the
United States, Japan, Greece and South Korea.
</P>
<P>
Physicist Wolfgang Pauli first proposed in 1930 the existence
of a neutral particle, later named "neutrino," for "little neutral
one," by Enrico Fermi. Experiments since have demonstrated the
existence of two species of neutrinos, the electron neutrino and
the muon neutrino, and suggested the existence of a third species.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000722.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cheney Becomes Leading Candidate for Bush Running Mate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 21 (Xinhua) -- U.S. former Defense Secretary
Dick Cheney has become the leading candidate for the running mate
of Republican presidential candidate George W. Bush, an AP report
said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted a Republican official as saying that Bush is
"very very close" to select Cheney, head of Bush's vice
presidential selection team, as his running mate.
</P>
<P>
The official, however, cautioned that Bush has not made his
final decision yet, but he is likely to make up his mind as early
as Monday, a week before the opening of the Republican National
Convention in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
Cheney, a Texas businessman, has changed his voter registration
from Texas to Wyoming to make him eligible to run with Bush, the
two-term Texas governor.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Constitution forbids the Electoral College voters in
Texas from voting for both the president and vice president who
are "inhabitants" of their state. Cheney
</P>
<P>
Cheney served as defense secretary under Bush's father, former
President George Bush, from 1989-93 and successfully cut defense
spending in his tenure. He was also a key strategist in the Gulf
War.
</P>
<P>
A respected public figure with a long record of service, Cheney,
59, would be a low-risk pick, but his health would be a question
with three mild heart attacks by the age of 48, AP said.
</P>
<P>
He was mentioned as a possible vice presidential running mate
for the older Bush in 1992. 
</P>
</TEXT>
