<HEADLINE> G-8 Leaders Adopt IT Charter in Okinawa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OKINAWA, Japan, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Leaders of the Group of
Eight (G-8) major nations on Saturday adopted a charter to deal
with the rapid development of information technology at their
second-day session of the annual summit in Nago, Okinawa.
</P>
<P>
The "IT Charter" aims at promoting the growth of IT and IT-
derived macroeconomies and maximizing their positive economic
impacts, while setting up provisions to actively cope with
possible risks.
</P>
<P>
The charter incorporates measures for seizing opportunity and
bridging the "digital divide" between rich and poor people and
countries.
</P>
<P>
It also calls for efforts to forge international rules on IT-
related business activities.
</P>
<P>
The G-8 comprises Britain, Canada, France, Germany, Italy,
Japan, Russia and the United States. The three-day Okinawa summit
is the first summit to take up IT as a major issue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
