<HEADLINE> Medical Biotechnology Benefits Millions of Patients </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Some 270 million people
worldwide have benefited from biotech drugs and vaccines,
according to a report released Friday.
</P>
<P>
"The first medical biotech product is less than 20 years old
and already 270 million patients have been helped by this
technology," said the report from the U.S.-based Biotechnology
Industry Organization (BIO), which represents some 900 companies,
academic institutions and biotech centers in 26 nations.
</P>
<P>
The BIO has conducted a study based on the approximate number
of people who have been helped directly by biotech drugs and
vaccines currently on the market. Biotech drugs and vaccines are
classified as those medicines developed through cellular or
molecular processes.
</P>
<P>
The rapid progress demonstrates the potential of the young
industry to develop cures and therapies for debilitating diseases
such as heart disease, Alzheimer's, Parkinson's and various forms
of cancer, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The biotechnology industry currently has more than 350
medicines in late-stage clinical trials. Nearly 100 biotech drugs
and vaccines have been approved by the U.S. Food and Drug
Administration, according to the BIO.
</P>
<P>
Non-medical applications of biotechnology are also contributing
to the quality of life for people worldwide, the BIO said.
Agricultural biotech products are helping farmers produce stronger
and healthier crops and industrial biotech products are making
manufacturing cleaner and more efficient.
</P>
<P>
In the United States, the BIO said, the biotechnology industry,
which as a whole remains unprofitable, makes substantial
contributions to the economy. Altogether, biotech companies
generated more than 430,000 jobs and 47 billion U.S. dollars in
revenues in 1999. Biotech firms' spending on research and
development totaled 11 billion dollars, and their tax revenues
amounted 10 billion dollars in the same year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000722.0139 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian Rail Companies Strike Deal to Share Resources </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Canadian Pacific Railway (CPR) of
Montreal and Calgary-based Canadian National Railway (CN)
announced two deals Friday for sharing rail corridors in eastern
North America.
</P>
<P>
In a joint statement, the former rivals said the agreements
were aimed at improving efficiency while keeping strong
competition between the two historic railways.
</P>
<P>
Under a five-year agreement, CN will be allowed to move forest
products and some other commodities from Quebec, Canada, to
destinations as far as New York City, Albany, Philadelphia and
Scranton in the eastern part of the United States.
</P>
<P>
CPR will receive reciprocal haulage from CN to ship the same
commodities into Ontario, Quebec and the Maritimes in eastern
Canada.
</P>
<P>
The two companies also agreed on a three-year deal for sharing
CN's busy Toronto-Chicago corridor, according to the joint
statement.
</P>
<P>
The announcement came a day after CN and U.S. rail giant
Burlington Northern Santa Fe killed their seven-month-old merger
proposal because of a time-consuming moratorium imposed on the
deal on the part of the United States. The deal would have created
the continent's largest railway. 
</P>
</TEXT>
