<HEADLINE> G-8 Leaders Begin Second-Day Session in Okinawa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OKINAWA, Japan, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Leaders of the Group of
Eight (G-8) major nations began the second-day session of their
annual summit in Nago, Okinawa, on Saturday morning with the aim
of working out a charter to deal with the rapidly advancing
information technology (IT).
</P>
<P>
The "IT Charter," to be adopted at the end of the morning
session, is expected to call for efforts to forge international
rules on IT-related business activities.
</P>
<P>
It will also incorporate measures for seizing opportunities and
bridging the "digital divide" between rich and poor people and
countries.
</P>
<P>
Highlighting the initiative will be the establishment of a task
force to follow up and coordinate policies and activities among
governments, non-governmental organizations and private companies.
</P>
<P>
Besides economic issues, the G-8 leaders are also expected to
confirm their stepped-up fight against AIDS and other infectious
diseases, and set numerical targets for their eventual eradication.
</P>
<P>
The three-day summit at the Bankoku Shinryokan hall in this
central Okinawa city brings together the leaders of Britain,
Canada, France, Germany, Italy, Japan, Russia and the United
States. 
