<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Camp David Talks Slow for Jewish Sabbath </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 21 (Xinhua) -- The three-way Middle East peace
talks at Camp David near Washington slowed down on Friday with the
beginning of the Jewish Sabbath.
</P>
<P>
Following 11 days of intensive discussions, negotiators from
the U.S., Israel and Palestine had agreed to hold a pick-up
basketball game after sunset.
</P>
<P>
Describing this as a "new development," U.S. State Department
spokesman Richard Boucher said earlier Friday that "the teams will
be mixed up between Americans, Palestinians and Israelis, ...
they're not divided up into sides."
</P>
<P>
Despite the lessening formality of the talks, Boucher said the
parties remained serious and committed to reaching a peace
agreement.
</P>
<P>
"Serious efforts are under way by the negotiators, led by their
leadership, to try to deal with these (final status) issues," he
said.
</P>
<P>
During daytime Friday, Boucher said, small groups of
negotiators continued to discuss the core issues of Israeli-
Palestinian conflict at the U.S. presidential retreat in Maryland.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, who stepped in when
President Bill Clinton is away in Japan for a summit of
industrialized countries, participated in some of the group
discussions, he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, it was reported that Clinton has rearranged his
schedule in Japan to return a few hours earlier than scheduled on
Sunday afternoon to continue his mediation at Camp David. 
</P>
</TEXT>
