<DOCNO> XIE20000722.0143 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China: Top of the Week (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
-- Dozens of Chinese scholars urged that the rampant damage
being done to ancient cities be stopped and that officials
responsible for such activities be investigated according to law.
</P>
<P>
The experts from the State Cultural Relics Bureau and other
departments revealed at a seminar on protecting ancient cities
that a number of important historical cities are being seriously
damaged to pave the way for urban construction and infrastructure
building.
</P>
<P>
The scholars listed a number of other ancient cities that have
been disfigured, including Guiyang, an important city in the
history of the Long March, and Xiangfan, where there was once a 1,
000-year-old wall.
</P>
<P>
-- Computer-related disciplines have become the favorites of
this year's university and college candidates, instead of finance
and administration that were hot" in the past.
</P>
<P>
Nearly one out of every five respondents chose computer
application and software development as their college majors.
</P>
<P>
The ratio is higher -- up to 29.4 percent -- in China's four
major cities of Beijing, Shanghai, Tianjin and Chongqing.
</P>
<P>
Physics and medicine, though the most favored by the parents of
these students, rank second, with a ratio of 7.6 percent, 12.5
percentage points lower than computers.
</P>
<P>
-- China will start construction of a 703-km-long gas pipeline
extending from southwest China's Sichuan Province to Hubei
Province in central China before the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
The gas pipeline, expected to be completed by early 2003, is
part of the country's huge project of sending gas from west to
east. The main part of the pipeline starts at Zhongxian County in
Chongqing, the largest metropolis in southwest China, and ends in
Wuhan, capital of Hubei, with an investment totaling 2.9 billion
yuan.
</P>
<P>
-- The China Federation of Literary and Art Circles (CFLAC)
kicked off its official website for spreading news of the state's
artists and cultural progress.
</P>
<P>
The website, chinabao.com, which is jointly promoted by the
CFLAC and Beijing Telecom, covers literature, performing arts,
visual arts and audio arts.
</P>
<P>
The website also features on-line exhibitions, purchase,
auction, education and a database of well-known Chinese artists.
</P>
<P>
-- China issued a 10-page technical guideline on urban garbage
disposal, in a bid to tackle the pollution caused by the country's
growing mountains of domestic garbage.
</P>
<P>
The policy calls for measures to reduce the amount of garbage
discharged in urban areas, including discouraging the practice of
excessive packaging, and promoting clean vegetables and clean fuel
for urban residents.
</P>
<P>
According to the policy, local governments are encouraged to
choose the right garbage disposal technology and equipment that
best suits local conditions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000722.0144 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China: Top of the Week (4) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
-- The State Postal Bureau (SPB) signed agreements with 14
companies, include Dell and Haier, to provide e-commerce logistic
services for them.
</P>
<P>
This move indicates that the bureau has made a decision to play
a major role in the burgeoning e-commerce business.
</P>
<P>
The SPB has 236 large delivery centers across the country,
linking more than 2,300 cities and counties. Besides, its mailing
trunk line links all the cities in the country, and is connected
with more than 200 countries.
</P>
<P>
-- China Unicom, the country's second largest provider of
telecommunications services, opened its Internet service by
opening the port website www.cnuninet.com.
</P>
<P>
The China Unicom Network will have international digital ports
in Beijing, Shanghai and Guangzhou.
</P>
<P>
China Unicom was listed on the New York and Hong Kong stock
exchanges last month. Set up in 1993 and grew rapidly with strong
support from the government, the company now boasts 14 percent of
the Chinese domestic market, and its mobile Telecom network
subscribers had reached 10.1 million as of June this year.
</P>
<P>
-- China will succeed in controlling its population below 1.3
billion as planed by the end of this year, according to a report
by population experts.
</P>
<P>
The report by a group of experts from the Chinese Academy of
Social Sciences and the State Family Planning Commission said
China's total population was 1.258 billion by the end of last
September.
</P>
<P>
The current population growth rate in China is below 1 percent,
one of the lowest in the world's developing countries.China's
population has been well under control since the family-planning
policy was adopted in 1970s, and the country has been experiencing
an ideal period characterized by "low birthrate, low death rate
low growth rate" since late 1990s, the experts said.
</P>
<P>
-- China will liberalize the interest rates system in about
three years.
</P>
<P>
Dai Xianglong, Governor the People's Bank of Chinas said that
the country does plan to liberalize the interest rates. So far,
the interest rates for foreign currencies and those for inter-bank
lending have been opened.
</P>
<P>
The next move will be liberalizing the lending interest rates
in rural areas. "For the urban areas, we will first widen the
floating extent of loans," he said.
</P>
<P>
As for the deposits, interest rates of wholesale deposits will
first be opened and other kinds of deposits will follow.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
