<DOCNO> XIE20000722.0145 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China: Top of the Week (5) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
-- A new regulation meant to improve safety products used for
individuals and property was jointly issued by the State Bureau of
Quality and Technical Supervision and the Ministry of Public
Security.
</P>
<P>
The security products, including anti-theft doors, bullet-proof
vests, alarm systems and other anti-burglary devices are necessary
for protecting society.
</P>
<P>
Unlicensed or unauthenticated security-related products are
forbidden to be produced, sold or used. Violators face warnings or
fines.
</P>
<P>
The regulation goes into effect on September 1.
</P>
<P>
-- The summer attack of locusts has been brought under control
thanks to the concentrated efforts of central and local
governments.
</P>
<P>
Agricultural experts said that while the threat of locusts to
this autumn's crops still exists, the worst is over.
</P>
<P>
This summer, huge swarms of locusts assaulted farmland in 16
provinces, autonomous regions and municipalities, covering a total
area of six million hectares. In severely-affected areas, mostly
in northern China, 1,000-5,000 locusts were found per square meter
on average.
</P>
<P>
So far, central and local governments have spent over 60
million yuan in the nationwide fight against locusts on two
million hectares of farmland, with an effectiveness rate of about
90 percent.
</P>
<P>
-- China's registered domain names have increased by 20 times
within the past two years.
</P>
<P>
Up to June 2000, China's network users have reached the mark of
10 million, with registered domain names ending with cn" amounting
to 99,734. Whereas at the end of 1997, the figures were only 620,
000 and 4,066 respectively.
</P>
<P>
According to the report of China Internet Network Information
Center (CNNIC) -- the national administration of domain
registration, domain names, or registered on-line trademarks and
identification cards, are becoming indispensable resources for
enterprises as Internet and e-business are gaining popularity.
</P>
<P>
-- The State Bureau of Quality and Technical Supervision has
issued an emergency decree ordering localities to step up
supervision of the production and trading of fireworks, boilers
and pressure containers.
</P>
<P>
Alarmed at the frequent occurrence of industrial accidents
across the country in the past several months, the bureau has
issued a series of circulars concerning the safety of these
products.
</P>
<P>
The new circular orders enterprises that have not met the
safety rules to rectify within a set term. It says that units that
can not reach the official safety requirements within the set term
must halt their operations or have their business licenses revoked.
Strict checks must be made on all the premises and facilities that
are involved in the manufacturing, trading or storing of dangerous
goods. Only those that are guaranteed safe may resume operations,
the decree says.
</P>
<P>
-- China will focus on developing both traditional Chinese
medicine and bio-engineered medicine in the coming five years,
hoping to become one of the world's pharmaceutical giants.
</P>
<P>
About 200 Chinese academic institutes and 140 manufacturers are
researching and developing bio-medicine. More than 20 kinds of
high-tech drugs have been churned out with three billion yuan (361
million U.S. dollars) worth of annual output.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics released by the SETC, the nationwide
pharmaceutical industry in 1999 saw profits of 11.1 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-four enterprises gained returns of over 100 million yuan
each. Tianjin Pharmaceutical Group, 999 Enterprise Group and
Tianjin Smith-Kline Beecham (SB) Pharmaceutical Corporation were
ranked as the top three. 
</P>
</TEXT>
