<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian President Rueful Over Fallout From Sacking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 22 (Xinhua) -- A day after his scathing attack on
the House of Representatives (DPR), Indonesian President
Abdurrahman Wahid Friday offered his apology with the legislative
body to let the interpellation matter rest in order to reduce
political tension in the country.
</P>
<P>
In a letter sent Friday evening to the House, Wahid insisted he
had already expressed his regret despite the House's demand for an
apology.
</P>
<P>
"In all sincerity, once again I'm sorry for all the effects
that should not have happened," he said, according to a copy of
the letter delivered to House Speaker Akbar Tanjung.
</P>
<P>
Akbar read out the gist of the letter latter in Friday evening.
</P>
<P>
"I hope this (gesture) will be well received by all and marks
the start of an attempt to reduce tension and to build better
relations between us all," the president said in the letter.
</P>
<P>
The row with the House was prompted by his response at the
House on Thursday to an interpellation motion to answer questions
about his reasons for firing two ministers in April.
</P>
<P>
The president said the use of the interpellation motion,
submitted under a 1999 law, was a betrayal of the 1945
Constitution and that he was not under any obligation to answer
the House summons. The president refused to answer five questions
posed to him by the House.
</P>
<P>
Wahid's statement triggered angry and disappointments among
parliamentarians. Accusing of arrogant and not cooperative, some
parliamentarians demand the president to apologize to the House or
facing another motion.
</P>
<P>
Speaker of the House Akbar Tandjung said after the Thursday
meeting that the House will wait a comprehensive written answer
from the president by Friday afternoon at the latest.
</P>
<P>
"If the House does not satisfy with the response, we can file
another motion," Tandjung told reporters.
</P>
<P>
In April, the president dismissed two ministers, namely
Minister of Investment Laksamana Sukardi of the Indonesian
Democratic Party of Struggle and Minister of Trade and Industry
Jusuf Kalla of the Golkar Party. Wahid said he fired them because
they were corrupt.
</P>
<P>
The two former ministers denied the accusations and angry
colleagues in the House then instigated the interpellation motion.
</P>
</TEXT>
