<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Dominates Men's Doubles in Indonesia Badminton Open </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia maintained its supremacy
in the men's doubles while their women's singles seeded players
suffered upset in the quarter-finals of the Sanyo Indonesia Open
here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
In the men's doubles, top seeded Candra Wijaya and Tony Gunawan
led Indonesia's campaign for the title. They fought tooth and
nail to beat Malaysian arch-rivals Choong Tan Fook and Lee Wan Wah
17-14, 15-11.
</P>
<P>
Sigit Budiarto and Halim Heryanto stole the attention of the
spectators in a thrilling match against Simon Archer and Nathan
Robertson of England. The Indonesian took the semifinals berth
after winning 15-13, 5-15, 15-9.
</P>
<P>
With Ricky Subagja/Rexy Mainaky and Flandy Limpele/Eng Hian
also making it to the semi-finals, Indonesia has now secured the
men's doubles crown.
</P>
<P>
In women's singles, former Indonesia's Uber Cup toast Mia
Audina, who is now playing for the Netherlands, became the biggest
seeded casualty as she was sent packing by her ex-teammate Lidya
Djaelawidjaja who won 8-11, 11-9, 11-0 for a place in Saturday's
semi-finals.
</P>
<P>
"I caught a cold after Thursday's match and I didn't feel well.
I'm not disappointed with the result. If I can't win here, I'll
focus my attention on the Olympic Games," the fourth-seedd Mia
said.
</P>
<P>
Lidya said: "I tried to play long rallies but Mia was very good
in her strokes. I was very tense in the first game but in the
second she was powerless and started to make unforced errors. In
the third game I played more relaxed."
</P>
<P>
Lidya will meet top seed Camilla Martin of Denmark, who had to
stretch muscles to defeat fifth seed Kanako Yonekura of Japan 11-4,
7-11, 11-5.
</P>
<P>
In another match, eighth seeded Marina Andrievskaya of Sweden
bowed out to Wang Chen of Hong Kong, China 6-11, 4-11. Wang will
play Kelly Morgan of Wales, who won over Judith Meulendijks of the
Netherlands 11-4, 11-1.
</P>
<P>
In the men's singles, giant killer Roslin Hashim of Malaysia
cruised to the semi-finals after eliminating Park Tae-sang of
South Korea 15-11, 15-8.
</P>
<P>
Roslin is scheduled to face Taufik Hidayat of Indonesia, who
had to struggle before overcoming Agus Hariyanto of Hong Kong,
China 12-15, 15-3, 15-11.
</P>
<P>
"The chance to win the event remains open wide. I have met
Taufik two times and I only won once," Roslin said.
</P>
<P>
The other semi-finals will see Johan Hadikusuma of Indonesia
against Ong Ewe Hock of Malaysia. Unseeded Johan fought
heroically against a nasty case of diarrhea Thursday evening
before eliminating Malaysian Yap Yong Jyen 15-8, 13-15, 15-8.
</P>
</TEXT>
