<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China: Top of the Week (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 22 (Xinhua) -- The following are the major
national news Xinhua released from July 15 to 21:
</P>
<P>
-- About 2.5 million public servants, about half of those hired
by local governments throughout China, have been laid off during
the ongoing government restructuring.
</P>
<P>
This was the latest update on the effort to streamline
government into a highly efficient force of expert civil servants.
The reform was first completed by the end of 1998 at State-level
agencies.
</P>
<P>
Central and local government staff once totaled 5.5 million.
During the central government level reform, the number of
employees was cut by half from 32,000 to 16,000, including nearly
40 ministers and over 550 bureau directors.
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese will have a chance to see a comet without using a
telescope in late July, according to Wang Sichao, a researcher at
the Nanjing's Purple Mountain Observatory attached to the Chinese
Academy of Sciences.
</P>
<P>
The comet, called "Nilier," is probably the only one that will
be visible to the naked eye this decade.
</P>
<P>
The comet was discovered by an astronomy research group at the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology on September 27 last year,
and it is thought to be non-periodic and revolving along a
hyperbolic orbit.
</P>
<P>
Called "passing traveler" by astronomers, the comet will never
be seen again from Earth after this, its first appearance.
</P>
<P>
-- People's Daily published a signed article condemning Li
Hongzhi's recent remarks.
</P>
<P>
The article says that Li has been spreading rumors to cheat the
people and instigate Falun Gong practitioners to confront with the
government.
</P>
<P>
The article accused Li of using malicious words to attack the
leadership of the Communist Party of China and the socialist
system, saying that Li's move has fully exposed that he is a
flunkey of the Western hostile forces.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000722.0156 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China: Top of the Week (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
-- Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji urged that the country should
improve its national defense while developing its economy.
</P>
<P>
Visiting a defense industry exhibition, Zhu urged that a
vigorous system be created to develop military science, and
nationwide cooperation be expanded in this regard by adhering to
the principle of self-reliance.
</P>
<P>
The premier stressed that the defense industry should be
combined with the civilian sector, and their cooperation should be
market-oriented. He noted that many military plants are suffering
losses due to the dogma of the planned economy.
</P>
<P>
-- China held a cultural activity at the Badaling section of
the Great Wall near Beijing to accelerate international cultural
exchanges.
</P>
<P>
The activity, which is expected to last one month, will invite
troupes from Russia, Japan and Kazakstan to give performances, and
Chinese troupes will perform dragon dances, lion dances and music
of the minority ethnic groups in China.
</P>
<P>
Art troupes will also display how warriors in ancient times
defended the wall against invaders at Badaling.
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese scientists have once again succeeded in forecasting
a powerful ionospheric storm, according to the China Electric Wave
Transmission Institute.
</P>
<P>
Beginning at zero hour on July 16, the ionospheric storm lasted
for over 20 hours and attacked many parts of the country,
resulting in a marked decline of the critical frequency of the
ionosphere, down over 50 percent in Manzhouli, in north China, and
Urumqi, the capital of the Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region, and
over 40 percent in Guangzhou, provincial capital of Guangdong, and
Haikou, provincial capital of Hainan, in the south.
</P>
<P>
-- China is developing a robot with hands for operations 6,000
meters underneath the surface of the sea, the first of its kind in
the world.
</P>
</TEXT>
