<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Science News: Weekly Highlights (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 22 (Xinhua) -- The following are the highlights
of major science stories released by Xinhua last week:
</P>
<P>
 Sino-Foreign Human Genome Research Project
</P>
<P>
 Launched in Shanghai
</P>
<P>
The Chinese National Human Genome Center (CHGC) and
pharmaceutical multinational Roche (China) signed an agreement for
co-operation in human genome research for schizophrenia and
diabetes.
</P>
<P>
CHGC Director Chen Zhu said it is the researchers' hope that
the project will help in the development of genic medicines for
the diseases, which are expected to become the major health risks
for China's growing aged population.
</P>
<P>
Roche will provide 300,000 U.S. dollars as well as technical
support and personnel training in the next three years for the
project.
</P>
<P>
 Chinese Students Win Gold Medals at Int'l Olympiads
</P>
<P>
Five Chinese high school students won five gold medals at the
31st International Physics Olympiad, and two gold, two silver
medals at the 11th International Biology Olympiad.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese students won the competition after they defeated
nearly 300 participants from other 63 countries and regions in the
31st Int'l Physics Olympiad, which was held in Britain from July 8
to 16, with their team scores ranking first.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, Wang Xu from Shandong and Song Zhentao from
Hunan won gold medals at the 11th Int'l Biology Olympiad in Turkey,
and Xu Liangliang from Hunan and Ye Jiangbin from Shaanxi attained
silver medals.
</P>
<P>
 China Developing Robot for 6,000-m Underwater Operations
</P>
<P>
China is developing a robot with hands for operations 6,000
meters underneath the surface of the sea, the first of its kind in
the world, its developer said in Shenyang, capital of northeast
China's Liaoning Province.
</P>
<P>
Wang Tianran, of the Shenyang Institute of Automation under the
Chinese Academy of Sciences, said the robot will be able to do
what existing robots can not do underwater, because it has hands.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Scientists Forecast Another Ionospheric Storm
</P>
<P>
Chinese scientists have once again succeeded in forecasting a
powerful ionospheric storm, according to the China Electric Wave
Transmission Institute.
</P>
<P>
The ionospheric storm was caused by a solar storm that occurred
on July 14 and began affecting the Earth. The ionospheric storm
lasted for over 20 hours, making it the longest of its kind felt
by the Earth in recent years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
