<HEADLINE> Chinese Science News: Weekly Highlights (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Modern science and technology have saved many aspects of
Tibetan medicine from being lost, according to an international
symposium on Tibetan medicine.
</P>
<P>
Modern science and technology can also help improve the
effectiveness of Tibetan medicine and the medical skills of
Tibetan doctors in treating diseases, according to experts who are
attending the three-day symposium on Tibetan medicine in this
capital of the Tibet Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
 Northwest University Involved in Hi-Tech Industrial
</P>
<P>
 Research
</P>
<P>
The Northwest China Engineering University has set up its own
technical research park in the New and Hi-tech Development Zone in
Xi'an, capital of northwest China's Shaanxi Province.
</P>
<P>
The park, with an area of some 73.3 ha, has accomplished the
first stage of construction work after four months, investing
nearly one billion yuan (about 120 million U.S. dollars) in 18
projects involving software, biology, education, materials,
machinery and electronics.
</P>
<P>
 China Sets Up New Micro-Electronics Lab
</P>
<P>
The Infineon-Fudan Lab, jointly set up by Fudan, a prestigious
university and Infineon Technology, a German semi-conductor giant,
became operational in Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
The opening of the lab signifies that China's micro-electronics
progress is up to the international standard.
</P>
<P>
 Scientific Research Helps Protect Rare Birds
</P>
<P>
Chinese scientists have made significant progress in rare bird
protection by artificially breeding certain protected species in
nature reserves.
</P>
<P>
Researchers at the Xianghai Nature Reserve in northeast China's
Jilin Province have successfully increased the population of such
rare birds as red-crowned cranes, white marabous and golden
vultures in this world-class swamp nature reserve through
artificial reproduction.  
</P>
</TEXT>
