<HEADLINE> Weekly Review of Top Legal News Events in China (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Beijing No. 2 Intermediate People's Court announced
recently the first-instance verdict in a spy case involving three
Taiwanese.
</P>
<P>
According to the court, Yang Mingzhong, Yao Jiazhen, and Zhang
Wei were spies hired by the military intelligence department of
Taiwan. They came to Beijing and Shanghai separately, attempting
to steal political, economic and military secrets in the
municipalities.
</P>
<P>
Corrupt Customs Official Sentenced to Death
</P>
<P>
A former customs official in east China's Zhejiang Province was
sentenced to death recently for taking bribes worth 1.8 million
yuan (about 216,867 US dollars).
</P>
<P>
The Hangzhou Intermediate Court handed down the death sentence
with a two-year reprieve.
</P>
<P>
Geng Yongxiang, 53, accepted bribes in RMB yuan and US dollars
as well as in the form of gifts such as jewelry when he acted as
director of the Suzhou Customs and later Hangzhou Customs from
1992 to 1999.
</P>
<P>
 China Openly Recruits Department-Level Officials
</P>
<P>
"Vote for me! Trust me to be capable of filling the post of
deputy director of the Anti-Corruption Bureau!"
</P>
<P>
The campaign speech by the first candidate Xu Jinhui drew
overwhelming applause from the 400-some audience in the meeting
hall of the Supreme People's Procuratorate (SPP).
</P>
<P>
Chinese Police to Enhance Int'l Cooperation in
</P>
<P>
Drug War
</P>
<P>
Chinese police will continue to strengthen cooperation with
their colleagues in other parts of the world to strike back
against international drug crime.
</P>
<P>
China's Public Security Minister Jia Chunwang made the above
remarks when addressing to Tuesday's opening ceremony of the Fifth
ICPO-Interpol Heroin Conference in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
 Collection of Macao's Legal Documents Published
</P>
<P>
A two-volume collection of the laws and legal documents in
effect in the Macao Special Administrative Region (SAR) was
published.
</P>
<P>
With a total of more than 3,300 pages, the collection includes
all the laws and administrative decrees effective in Macao up to
May this year. It is the first large-scale collection of law since
the Macao SAR was founded last December. 
</P>
</TEXT>
