<HEADLINE> Jury Rules Police Officer not Guilty for Hillsborough Soccer Disaster </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 21 (Xinhua) -- The jury in the case of two former
British policemen accused of manslaughter after the deaths of 96
Liverpool fans at Hillsborough soccer stadium in 1989 ruled on
Friday that one of the officers not guilty.
</P>
<P>
Ex-Superintendent Bernard Murray was found not guilty of
manslaughter, a spokeswoman at Leeds Crown Court said.
</P>
<P>
The jury was still considering the charges against former Chief
Superintendent David Duckenfield who ran the policing operation.
</P>
<P>
The private prosecution by the Hillsborough Families Support
Group followed a government decision to turn down appeals for a
new inquiry into the deaths of the fans.
</P>
<P>
Lawyers for the families said the soccer fans died in a crush
after the two policemen allowed in more spectators than the
stadium capacity which led to a severe overcrowding in one of the
terraces.
</P>
<P>
The disaster was the worst in British sporting history when the
fans died after being crushed against railings at the 1989 FA Cup
semi-final between Liverpool and Nottingham Forest at the stadium
in Sheffield, northern England. 
</P>
