<HEADLINE> Millennium Dome Won't Close Early </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Britain's Millennium Dome will
remain open until the end of the year and its management will not
seek a further Lottery bail-out, said the Dome's chief executive
on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Pierre-Yves Gerbeau was responding to reports that the Dome's
directors were so alarmed about its financial situation that they
had called in lawyers to advise them on whether they could
continue to trade.
</P>
<P>
It was suggested that Simmons &AMP; Simmons, insolvency specialists,
were called in by the 12-strong board amid fears that the New
Millennium Experience Company (NMEC) would not be financially
viable unless receipts increase.
</P>
<P>
Further speculation suggested the situation was so critical
that a further injection of 30 million pounds (48 million U.S.
dollars) was needed to keep the project afloat until the year's
end, the planned closure date.
</P>
<P>
In May, the Dome was bailed out with 29 million pounds of
Lottery money on the back of disappointing attendance numbers and
revenues.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, Gerbeau said: "As I've said many times before:
the Dome will be open for business until December 31 this year.
There is no question of an early closure. Our visitor numbers are
increasing - with superb levels of satisfaction -our costs are
down, and we are driving revenue up through food and merchandise
sales and corporate hospitality events."
</P>
<P>
The NMEC is now budgeting on having seven million visitors this
year - including one million free-admission schoolchildren.This
compares with the original estimate of 12 million visitors,which
was reduced to 10 million in February and then lowered to seven
million in May. 
</P>
</TEXT>
