of a car used by Sinn Fein leaders Gerry Adams and Martin
McGuinness.
</P>
<P>
The Cabinet Office Minister told a television programme to be
screened on Monday night that she approved the bugging of a car
used by the Sinn Fein leaders during last year's talks to resolve
the decommissioning and devolution dispute.
</P>
<P>
The surveillance device was discovered by Sinn Fein and
displayed at a Stormont press conference in December just days
after the formation of the Northern Ireland executive.
</P>
<P>
The incident was described by Adams as a "hugely serious breach
of faith" which could have damaged the peace process.
</P>
<P>
It was also condemned by the Irish Prime Minister Bertie Ahern
and Northern Ireland Deputy First Minister Seamus Mallon.
</P>
<P>
Northern Ireland Office officials, at the time, refused to
confirm military intelligence involvement in the incident.
</P>
<P>
However, Mowlam told BBC that the car was bugged in order to
save lives, with the driver believed to have been the target of
the security forces' operation. 
